"""
mkt-christ | Amos 1–5
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-amos-1-5.py

Christological arc:
  - Chs 1–2: Nations-oracle pattern → Paul's Romans 1–3 move; Christ as judge of nations and
    identifier with the crushed poor (2:6-8 → Matt 25); Davidic dynasty bears the judgment
    list's implicit promise of restoration.
  - Ch 3: Prophet-disclosure (3:7) → Christ as ultimate revealer (Rev 1:1); remnant typology (3:12).
  - Ch 4: Creator doxology (4:13) → Christ as creator; Sodom warning → Christ's greater warning;
    "Prepare to meet your God" → eschatological summons.
  - Ch 5: "Seek me and live" → Christ's invitation (John 5:24); Day-of-the-LORD darkness → cross;
    creator doxology (5:8); justice-stream (5:24) → eschatological kingdom justice.
  - Amos 9:11 (David's booth) already written; merge_comm skips it safely.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        existing.setdefault(ch, {})
        for v, html in verses.items():
            existing[ch].setdefault(v, html)

AMOS_CHRIST = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>Amos the sheep breeder (<em>nōqēd</em>) from Tekoa is the archetypal outsider-prophet: no priestly lineage, no official standing, called from agricultural labor to prophetic office. Jesus operates in the same pattern — from Nazareth rather than Jerusalem, from a carpenter&rsquo;s household rather than a priestly family, yet declaring words that carry divine authority (John 7:46). Amos&rsquo;s dates (Uzziah/Jeroboam II era, ca. 760–750 BCE) place the prophecy at Israel&rsquo;s height of material prosperity — the context in which prophetic judgment is most counterintuitive, just as Christ&rsquo;s strongest judgment-words come to the prosperous religious establishment of his day.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A title: &ldquo;The LORD roars from Zion.&rdquo; The lion-roar of YHWH — judgment voiced from Jerusalem — is taken up in Revelation and applied to Christ: &ldquo;the Lion of the tribe of Judah, the Root of David, has conquered&rdquo; (Rev 5:5). The one who roars in judgment in Amos is the same Lord who appears in Revelation as the slain Lamb-and-Lion. YHWH&rsquo;s word from Zion that withers the pastures typologically anticipates Christ&rsquo;s word, which both nourishes and judges: &ldquo;the word that I have spoken will judge him on the last day&rdquo; (John 12:48).</p>",
    "3": "<p>A type: the oracle-formula &ldquo;For three crimes of X, and for four, I will not revoke judgment&rdquo; — the graded numerical sequence signals escalating, accumulated guilt past the point of mercy. The NT teaches the same structure: repeated rejection of grace accumulates to final judgment (Heb 6:4-8; 10:26-31). Damascus&rsquo;s crime is violence against Gilead with iron threshing sledges — the crushing of the vulnerable. Christ, who identifies himself with the crushed (Matt 25:40: &ldquo;what you did to one of the least of these, you did to me&rdquo;), is the judge whose verdict on such violence is absolute.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A shadow: fire on the house of Hazael and the fortresses of Ben-hadad. The judgment on the Aramaean dynasty is the dissolution of imperial power that has used violence against the innocent. The NT&rsquo;s eschatology extends this pattern to all worldly empires: &ldquo;the kingdoms of the world have become the kingdom of our Lord and of his Christ&rdquo; (Rev 11:15). Every fortress that has been built through oppression will fall under the same judgment that Amos announces to Damascus.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A shadow: breaking the gate-bar of Damascus — the cutting off of rulers and officials. The scepter-bearer (<em>tōmēk shēveṭ</em>) of Beth-eden falls. Against this pattern of broken earthly authority stands Christ&rsquo;s authority: &ldquo;all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me&rdquo; (Matt 28:18). Human dynasties and official power structures are fragile before divine judgment; Christ&rsquo;s kingdom alone is unshakeable (Heb 12:28).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A type: Gaza&rsquo;s crime is mass deportation — whole communities handed over to Edom as slaves. The removal of persons from their land and people is the extreme form of dehumanization. Christ&rsquo;s work is the reversal of exile and deportation: he gathers the scattered (John 11:52: &ldquo;to gather into one the children of God who are scattered abroad&rdquo;). The judgment on the slave-trade is the ground on which Christ&rsquo;s reconciling work stands — he restores what violence scatters.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A shadow: fire on the wall of Gaza consuming her fortresses. The military infrastructure of Gaza — the defensive walls built to protect a city whose economy included slave-trading — will be destroyed. The NT uses fire-imagery for eschatological judgment (2 Thess 1:7-8; Rev 20:9). The particularization of judgment to specific cities in Amos is the prophetic ground for Revelation&rsquo;s particularized judgment on specific powers that have opposed God&rsquo;s purposes.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A shadow: the cutting off of Ashdod&rsquo;s ruler and Ashkelon&rsquo;s scepter-bearer, with YHWH&rsquo;s hand turned against Ekron. The Philistine city-states collapse before divine judgment. Christologically: the ultimate Philistine victory — David&rsquo;s defeat of Goliath — becomes the type for Christ&rsquo;s defeat of the powers (Col 2:15: &ldquo;disarming the rulers and authorities, he put them to open shame, triumphing over them&rdquo;). The defeat of the Philistine system is the shadow of Christ&rsquo;s victory over all hostile spiritual and political powers.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A type: Tyre&rsquo;s crime is betraying an alliance (<em>bĕrît ʾaḥîm</em>, &ldquo;covenant of brothers&rdquo;) and handing over a whole community to Edom. The violation of covenant-brotherhood is the deepest social sin. Jesus elevates covenant-brotherhood to its highest form: &ldquo;you are my friends if you do what I command you&rdquo; (John 15:14); &ldquo;he who is not with me is against me&rdquo; (Matt 12:30). The betrayal of covenant-bonds is also the specific sin of Judas at the Last Supper — the covenant-meal broken by the one who sells a covenant-brother.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A shadow: fire on the wall of Tyre. Tyre was the commercial empire of the ancient Mediterranean — its wealth and its judgment become the type for Revelation&rsquo;s &ldquo;Babylon the Great&rdquo; (Rev 18:2-3), the commercial and political power that &ldquo;made all nations drink the wine of the passion of her sexual immorality.&rdquo; Ezekiel 26-28 extends the Tyre judgment into an extended eschatological symbol, and Revelation draws on both Amos and Ezekiel in its final judgment narrative.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A type: Edom&rsquo;s crime — pursuing his brother with the sword, suppressing all compassion, maintaining perpetual anger. The Edom-Israel enmity is the Esau-Jacob conflict in national form: the rejected brother who will not forgive. The NT resolution is in Christ: &ldquo;For he himself is our peace, who has made us both one and has broken down in his flesh the dividing wall of hostility&rdquo; (Eph 2:14). Edom represents the hardened heart that refuses reconciliation — the opposite of the Father who runs to the returning prodigal (Luke 15:20).</p>",
    "12": "<p>A shadow: fire on Teman and the fortresses of Bozrah — the destruction of Edom&rsquo;s strongholds. Isaiah 63:1-6 takes up the Bozrah imagery in a vision of the divine warrior coming from Edom in judgment, staining his garments red — an image that Revelation applies to the returning Christ (Rev 19:13: &ldquo;he is clothed in a robe dipped in blood&rdquo;). Amos&rsquo;s fire on Bozrah is thus the early note in a prophetic chord that Revelation resolves in Christ.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A type: Ammon&rsquo;s crime — ripping open pregnant women in Gilead to expand their territory. The most extreme form of violence against the most vulnerable, for the sake of territorial ambition. Jesus&rsquo;s harshest judgment-words are reserved for those who harm the vulnerable and the young: &ldquo;whoever causes one of these little ones to sin — it would be better for him if a great millstone were hung around his neck&rdquo; (Matt 18:6). The logic of Amos&rsquo;s oracle is exactly this: crimes against the most vulnerable provoke the most unrelenting divine response.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A shadow: fire on the wall of Rabbah — amid battle cries on the day of war. The political structure of Ammon falls under divine judgment because it was built through systematic atrocity. The Day-of-battle imagery (shouts, storm, whirlwind) connects to the NT&rsquo;s day-of-wrath language (Rom 2:5: &ldquo;the day of wrath when God&rsquo;s righteous judgment will be revealed&rdquo;). Christ, who bore divine wrath on behalf of those who trust him, is also the one who executes final judgment on those who persist in the Ammonite pattern.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A shadow: the Ammonite king goes into exile with his officials. The pattern of empire going into exile is reversed in Christ: rather than the covenant people going into exile, the hostile powers themselves are expelled. &ldquo;Then he will say to those on his left, &lsquo;Depart from me, you cursed&rsquo;&rdquo; (Matt 25:41) — the exile sentence is pronounced on those who persisted in the Ammonite pattern of disregarding the vulnerable.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>A type: Moab&rsquo;s crime — burning the bones of the king of Edom to lime. Desecrating the dead, even an enemy&rsquo;s dead, violates a fundamental human dignity that crosses all national boundaries. This offense against a corpse signals that Moab has forfeited its humanity in its hatred. Christ&rsquo;s burial is attended with spices and honor even amid the shame of crucifixion (John 19:39-40); and his resurrection overcomes the ultimate dishonor of death. The divine care for the body even in judgment is implicit in Amos&rsquo;s condemnation of desecration.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A shadow: fire on Moab, consuming the fortresses of Kerioth; Moab falls in turmoil. The collapse of Moab under judgment is part of the nations-oracle sequence in which all human imperial arrangements fall. The NT&rsquo;s eschatological vision of the nations at the Last Day (Matt 25:32: &ldquo;all the nations will be gathered before him&rdquo;) gives the Amos oracles their ultimate scope — not just Aram, Gaza, Tyre, Edom, Ammon, and Moab, but all nations stand before the Son of Man.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A shadow: the ruler and all his princes are cut off. The comprehensive fall of Moab&rsquo;s leadership echoes the NT&rsquo;s declaration that all earthly authority is provisional and subordinate: &ldquo;Then comes the end, when he delivers the kingdom to God the Father after destroying every rule and every authority and power&rdquo; (1 Cor 15:24). Christ&rsquo;s reign is the last act of this nations-oracle drama.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A type: Judah&rsquo;s crime — rejecting the law of the LORD and not keeping his statutes, following lies. The inclusion of Judah in the oracle-sequence is the literary trap: Israel has been listening to judgment on surrounding nations with satisfaction, only to find the charges escalate to include the covenant people. This is the rhetorical move Paul executes in Romans 1–3: Gentile sin (ch. 1) → Jewish sin (ch. 2) → &ldquo;all have sinned&rdquo; (3:23). Christ is the one who fulfills what Judah failed to fulfill: &ldquo;Do not think that I have come to abolish the Law or the Prophets; I have not come to abolish them but to fulfill them&rdquo; (Matt 5:17).</p>",
    "5": "<p>A shadow: fire on Judah consuming the fortresses of Jerusalem. The destruction of Jerusalem&rsquo;s defenses — whether by Nebuchadnezzar in 586 BCE or, in Jesus&rsquo;s prediction, by Rome in 70 CE — is the outcome of covenant unfaithfulness. Christ weeps over Jerusalem: &ldquo;Would that you, even you, had known on this day the things that make for peace! But now they are hidden from your eyes&rdquo; (Luke 19:41-42). Amos&rsquo;s fire-on-Jerusalem and Jesus&rsquo;s lament are the same prophetic grief — that the covenant city does not recognize its covenant Lord.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A fulfillment-context: Israel&rsquo;s crime — selling the righteous for silver and the poor for a pair of sandals. This verse launches the most famous section of Amos: Israel&rsquo;s social injustice as covenant violation. Christ&rsquo;s identification with the poor is the direct NT counterpart: &ldquo;Truly I say to you, as you did it to one of the least of these my brothers, you did it to me&rdquo; (Matt 25:40). The selling of the righteous for silver also echoes Judas&rsquo;s betrayal of Christ for thirty pieces of silver — the price of a slave (Matt 26:15; Zech 11:12-13).</p>",
    "7": "<p>A type: trampling the heads of the poor into the dust and pushing the afflicted off the road; father and son going to the same woman, defiling YHWH&rsquo;s name. The poor are physically pushed aside to make way for the wealthy; the covenant&rsquo;s sexual ethics are violated. Jesus begins his ministry announcing good news to the poor (Luke 4:18) and consistently places the crushed and the marginalized at the center of his kingdom — the reversal of exactly this pattern. The dishonor of YHWH&rsquo;s name through social injustice is reversed in Christ, who hallows the Father&rsquo;s name by embodying justice.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A type: garments taken in pledge spread out beside every altar; wine from fines drunk in the house of their God. The pledged garment was property that belonged to the poor (Exod 22:26-27: the creditor must return a debtor&rsquo;s cloak by nightfall, for it is his covering). Using it as altar-furniture while drinking wine extracted through unjust fines is a double sacrilege: exploitation plus false worship. Jesus&rsquo;s cleansing of the temple (John 2:13-17) addresses the same fusion of commercial exploitation and official worship — turning the house of prayer into a den of robbers.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A type: YHWH destroyed the Amorite — tall as cedars, strong as oaks, destroyed root and branch. The conquest narrative is invoked to establish YHWH&rsquo;s saving history as the ground on which his current charge against Israel rests. Christ brings the same rhetorical move: &ldquo;You search the Scriptures because you think that in them you have eternal life; and it is they that bear witness about me&rdquo; (John 5:39). Israel&rsquo;s salvation history — Exodus, conquest, prophets — all bears witness to the one who is the ground and goal of that history.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A type: &ldquo;I also brought you up from the land of Egypt, led you through the wilderness forty years, and gave you the land of the Amorite.&rdquo; The Exodus-and-wilderness-and-inheritance sequence is the OT&rsquo;s master-narrative of redemption. The NT reads Christ as fulfilling this pattern: he is the new Moses who leads the new Exodus (Luke 9:31: &ldquo;his departure [<em>exodon</em>] which he was about to accomplish at Jerusalem&rdquo;); he passes through the wilderness forty days (Matt 4:1-11); he gives the new inheritance (&ldquo;blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth,&rdquo; Matt 5:5).</p>",
    "11": "<p>A type: YHWH raised up prophets from Israel&rsquo;s sons and Nazirites from Israel&rsquo;s young men. The prophetic and Nazirite offices were YHWH&rsquo;s gifts to Israel — channels of revelation and consecration. Christ is the fulfillment of both: the Prophet greater than Moses (Deut 18:15; Acts 3:22) and, in Luke 1:35, consecrated from birth in a manner that parallels the Nazirite dedication (though not identical to the Mosaic Nazirite law). When Israel despised these gifts (v. 12), they were preparing the rejection of the Prophet himself: &ldquo;He came to his own, and his own people did not receive him&rdquo; (John 1:11).</p>",
    "12": "<p>A type: &ldquo;But you gave the Nazirites wine to drink and commanded the prophets, &lsquo;Do not prophesy.&rsquo;&rdquo; The silencing of the prophets is the pattern of Israel&rsquo;s history that Jesus explicitly invokes: &ldquo;Woe to you, for you build the tombs of the prophets whom your fathers killed&rdquo; (Luke 11:47). Jerusalem is the city that kills the prophets and stones those sent to her (Matt 23:37). The command &ldquo;Do not prophesy&rdquo; reaches its ultimate expression in the Sanhedrin&rsquo;s command to Jesus&rsquo;s disciples: &ldquo;that they speak no more to anyone in this name&rdquo; (Acts 4:17-18).</p>",
    "13": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Watch — I will crush you in your tracks, as a cart loaded with sheaves presses down.&rdquo; The crushing weight of judgment against Israel who has crushed the poor is a form of divine lex talionis — the same crushing comes back on the crushers. Christ is the one who has borne this weight: &ldquo;Surely he has borne our griefs and carried our sorrows&rdquo; (Isa 53:4); he was crushed for our iniquities (Isa 53:5 <em>mĕdukkāʾ</em>). The judgment-weight that Amos announces lands on Christ on behalf of those who trust him.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Flight will fail the swift, the strong will find no strength, and the warrior will not escape with his life.&rdquo; The comprehensive futility of escape from YHWH&rsquo;s judgment is the NT&rsquo;s message about the final day: &ldquo;from the presence of him who is seated on the throne and from the wrath of the Lamb, for the great day of their wrath has come, and who can stand?&rdquo; (Rev 6:16-17). The inescapability of judgment that Amos announces about Israel in the Assyrian crisis becomes in Revelation the pattern of the last judgment from which no earthly power provides refuge.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A shadow: bowman, swift soldier, and horseman alike cannot escape. The military vocabulary exhausts the categories of human strength — all fail. The NT counterpart: &ldquo;There is no creature hidden from his sight, but all are naked and exposed to the eyes of him to whom we must give account&rdquo; (Heb 4:13). The only refuge from the divine judge is the divine judge himself, which is the paradox of the gospel: &ldquo;whoever hears my word and believes him who sent me has eternal life. He does not come into judgment&rdquo; (John 5:24).</p>",
    "16": "<p>A shadow: even the most courageous warrior flees naked on that day. The stripping of the warrior — the reversal of the military hero — is the ultimate humiliation. The great reversal of the Day of the LORD runs throughout the Prophets: the mighty are brought low (Isa 2:12-17; Luke 1:52). Christ is the one who was himself stripped and humiliated at Golgotha (John 19:23-24) so that the stripping of judgment might not fall on those who trust him; and who, in his return, strips away the pretensions of all false strength (Rev 19:11-16).</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Hear this word that the LORD has spoken against you, O people of Israel — against the whole family I brought up from the land of Egypt.&rdquo; The summons to &ldquo;hear&rdquo; (<em>shimʿu</em>) is the prophetic call to attention that the NT applies to Christ&rsquo;s proclamation: &ldquo;He who has ears, let him hear&rdquo; (Matt 11:15). The word against the whole family is simultaneously a claim of election and of covenant accountability — you are the family I saved, therefore you are responsible. The NT extension: Christ addresses the new covenant family — those brought up from the death of sin through his Exodus (Rom 6:3-4) — with the same combination of privilege and responsibility (1 Pet 1:17).</p>",
    "2": "<p>A type: &ldquo;You only have I known of all the families of the earth; therefore I will punish you for all your iniquities.&rdquo; The <em>yādaʿ</em> (know) here is the covenantal intimacy that founds accountability — the logic of greater privilege, greater responsibility. This verse is the OT foundation for Paul&rsquo;s argument in Romans 2:9-10: &ldquo;There will be tribulation and distress for every human being who does evil, the Jew first and also the Greek.&rdquo; In Christ, the elect&rsquo;s accountability is fully met — he bears the &ldquo;punishment for all your iniquities&rdquo; that the elect should receive, becoming the one who was fully known by God and fully punished on their behalf (2 Cor 5:21).</p>",
    "3": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Can two walk together unless they have agreed?&rdquo; The rhetorical questions of 3:3-8 all argue from cause to effect — no effect without a corresponding cause. YHWH&rsquo;s judgment is not arbitrary; it is the effect of Israel&rsquo;s refusal to walk with him. The covenant-walk is the OT&rsquo;s metaphor for ongoing relationship with God (Mic 6:8: &ldquo;walk humbly with your God&rdquo;). Christ is the one who walks with his disciples (Luke 24:15: &ldquo;Jesus himself drew near and went with them&rdquo;) and who makes agreement possible: &ldquo;I am the way&rdquo; (John 14:6) — the path on which the walk with God proceeds.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Does a lion roar in the forest when it has no prey?&rdquo; The logic of cause-and-effect continues. YHWH&rsquo;s roaring in v. 1:2 is not empty noise — there is a prey (Israel&rsquo;s sin). The lion-as-judge appears in the NT applied to Christ: the Lion of the tribe of Judah (Rev 5:5) who is simultaneously the Lamb who was slain. The same figure judges and redeems — the roar of Amos&rsquo;s lion is the sound of the same divine authority that, from the cross, declares &ldquo;It is finished&rdquo; (John 19:30).</p>",
    "5": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Does a bird fall to the ground in a snare when no trap has been set?&rdquo; The trap has been set — Israel&rsquo;s covenant-violations are the snare of their own making. The NT uses snare-imagery for the unexpected arrival of judgment: &ldquo;that day come upon you suddenly like a trap&rdquo; (Luke 21:34-35). The call to watchfulness in the Gospels (Matt 24:42-44) is the pastoral application of Amos&rsquo;s logical sequence: if the trap is set, the bird will fall; if judgment is coming, be ready.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;When a ram&rsquo;s horn sounds the alarm in a city, do the people not tremble? When disaster strikes a city, has not the LORD done it?&rdquo; The rhetorical question about YHWH&rsquo;s sovereignty over disaster is the OT&rsquo;s strong providentialism. The NT refines but does not abandon this: &ldquo;Are not two sparrows sold for a penny? And not one of them will fall to the ground apart from your Father&rdquo; (Matt 10:29). Christ is both the one through whom the Father&rsquo;s sovereignty operates and the one who faced the ultimate &ldquo;disaster&rdquo; — the crucifixion — in which God&rsquo;s judgment and mercy met.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A fulfillment: &ldquo;For the Lord GOD does nothing without first disclosing his plans to his servants the prophets.&rdquo; This is the OT&rsquo;s strongest statement of prophetic disclosure. Jesus takes up the same principle and claims its ultimate expression: &ldquo;No longer do I call you servants, for the servant does not know what his master is doing; but I have called you friends, for all that I have heard from my Father I have made known to you&rdquo; (John 15:15). The prophet-disclosure pattern of Amos 3:7 is fulfilled not merely in the writing prophets but in Christ, who reveals the Father fully (John 1:18: &ldquo;the only God, who is at the Father&rsquo;s side, he has made him known&rdquo;). Revelation 1:1 explicitly echoes Amos 3:7&rsquo;s structure: God reveals to his servant.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A type: &ldquo;The lion has roared — who will not be afraid? The Lord GOD has spoken — who can withhold prophecy?&rdquo; The compulsion of the prophetic word is the basis of prophetic authority — it cannot be suppressed. The apostles embody this: &ldquo;We cannot but speak of what we have seen and heard&rdquo; (Acts 4:20). The word of God that compels prophecy is ultimately the Word made flesh — Christ himself is the speaking of God that cannot be silenced even by death. The resurrection is YHWH&rsquo;s roar that demands response.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A shadow: Ashdod and Egypt are summoned to witness Israel&rsquo;s disorder and oppression — the pagan nations are called as witnesses against the covenant people. The irony: Israel, called to be a witness to the nations (Isa 43:10), is instead witnessed against by the nations. Christ reverses this: the church is now the witness to the nations (Acts 1:8: &ldquo;you will be my witnesses... to the end of the earth&rdquo;), testifying to the risen Lord rather than manifesting the disorder that Amos exposes.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;They do not know how to act with integrity — those who hoard violence and plunder in their strongholds.&rdquo; The not-knowing of Israel is a moral blindness, not merely an intellectual gap. Jesus applies the same diagnosis: &ldquo;Father, forgive them, for they do not know what they are doing&rdquo; (Luke 23:34) — the not-knowing of the crucifiers parallels Israel&rsquo;s moral blindness. The remedy for both is not information but transformation: &ldquo;the knowledge of the glory of God in the face of Jesus Christ&rdquo; (2 Cor 4:6).</p>",
    "11": "<p>A shadow: an enemy will surround the land, strip away the strongholds, and plunder the fortresses. The stripping of the strongholds that housed stolen wealth is the reversal of the hoarding condemned in v. 10. The pattern runs into the NT: the rich man&rsquo;s storehouses are torn down (Luke 12:18-20); the city built on plunder falls (Rev 18:11-13). Christ&rsquo;s own poverty — &ldquo;though he was rich, yet for your sake he became poor&rdquo; (2 Cor 8:9) — is the counterpoint to the strongholds that Israel filled with violence.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A type: as the shepherd rescues from the lion&rsquo;s mouth only two legs or a scrap of an ear, so a remnant of Israel will be saved. The remnant-typology is the OT&rsquo;s consistent pattern: not all Israel will perish; a small, humble remnant survives the lion&rsquo;s mouth. Paul applies this precisely: &ldquo;So too at the present time there is a remnant, chosen by grace&rdquo; (Rom 11:5). Christ is the good shepherd who loses none that the Father gives him (John 6:39) — the remnant preserved from the lion is the flock he carries on his shoulders (Luke 15:5).</p>",
    "13": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Hear this and testify against the house of Jacob, declares the Lord GOD, the God of armies.&rdquo; The summons to testimony against Jacob is the covenant lawsuit (<em>rîb</em>) pattern. The NT uses courtroom language for Christ&rsquo;s relation to Israel: &ldquo;Do not think that I will accuse you to the Father. There is one who accuses you: Moses, on whom you have set your hope&rdquo; (John 5:45). The accuser of Israel is the Law they profess to follow; Christ is simultaneously advocate (1 John 2:1) and judge (John 5:22).</p>",
    "14": "<p>A fulfillment-anticipation: &ldquo;On the day I call Israel to account for its crimes, I will also strike down the altars of Bethel.&rdquo; The false sanctuary at Bethel — set up by Jeroboam I as a rival to Jerusalem — falls under judgment alongside Israel&rsquo;s ethical crimes. Jesus&rsquo;s cleansing of the Jerusalem temple (John 2:13-22) and his prediction of its destruction (&ldquo;not one stone will be left on another,&rdquo; Matt 24:2) are the fulfillment of this pattern: the sanctuary that Israel has turned into an instrument of religious comfort for the comfortable will fall. Christ himself becomes the new temple (John 2:21).</p>",
    "15": "<p>A shadow: winter and summer houses demolished; houses adorned with ivory perish; great houses end. The luxury of Israel&rsquo;s ruling class — ivory-decorated houses that required the exploitation Amos condemns — will be stripped away. The NT&rsquo;s parable of Dives and Lazarus (Luke 16:19-31) is the same pattern compressed: the purple-clad rich man loses everything; the poor man is carried to Abraham&rsquo;s side. Christ&rsquo;s warning — &ldquo;woe to you who are rich, for you have received your consolation&rdquo; (Luke 6:24) — is Amos 3:15 applied to his own generation.</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Hear this word, you cows of Bashan on Mount Samaria — you who oppress the poor and crush the needy and say to your husbands, &lsquo;Bring us something to drink!&rsquo;&rdquo; Bashan was famous for its fattened livestock (Ps 22:12: &ldquo;strong bulls of Bashan surround me&rdquo;). Amos applies the image to Samaria&rsquo;s wealthy women who drive their husbands to oppress the poor in order to fund their feasting. The NT counterpart: the parable of the rich fool who says to his soul, &ldquo;Eat, drink, be merry&rdquo; (Luke 12:19), oblivious that the poor are dying at his gate. Christ&rsquo;s beatitude — &ldquo;blessed are the poor&rdquo; — is the reversal of the Bashan-cow prosperity ethic.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;The Lord GOD has sworn by his holiness: days are coming when they will drag you away with hooks — even the last of you with fishhooks.&rdquo; The oath by God&rsquo;s holiness is the strongest form of divine guarantee — YHWH&rsquo;s own character is pledged to the judgment. The fishermen-imagery (hooks/fishhooks) is reversed in Christ&rsquo;s call to his disciples: &ldquo;Follow me, and I will make you fishers of men&rdquo; (Matt 4:19). Amos&rsquo;s hooks catch the wealthy for judgment; Christ&rsquo;s nets catch the humble for salvation — the same imagery in precisely inverted operation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A shadow: the women of Samaria will be led out through breaches in the wall and thrown onto a dunghill. The imagery of being expelled through broken walls — the very walls built to protect privilege — is the eschatological pattern of judgment: what you built to protect your wealth becomes the route of your exile. Christ&rsquo;s parable of the banquet (Luke 14:21-24) has a similar logic: those invited from positions of privilege exclude themselves; the poor and crippled and lame enter through the open doors.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Come to Bethel and rebel; go to Gilgal and multiply your rebellion.&rdquo; The sarcastic invitation — come to the sanctuaries and sin — is prophetic irony at its sharpest. Both Bethel and Gilgal were sites of Israel&rsquo;s earliest covenant history that had been corrupted into centers of false worship. Jesus uses the same ironic mode with the Pharisees: &ldquo;You travel across sea and land to make a single proselyte, and when he becomes a proselyte, you make him twice as much a child of hell as yourselves&rdquo; (Matt 23:15). Religious observance without covenant faithfulness multiplies guilt rather than reducing it.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Offer your leavened thanksgiving sacrifices... announce your freewill offerings publicly.&rdquo; The public display of religiosity is what YHWH mocks: &ldquo;for so you love to do, O people of Israel!&rdquo; The love of visible piety is precisely what Jesus condemns: &ldquo;Beware of practicing your righteousness before other people in order to be seen by them&rdquo; (Matt 6:1). Leavened bread was explicitly excluded from the temple offerings (Lev 7:13 allows it for certain thanksgiving offerings but the point here is the corruption of the whole system). Religious performance without relational covenant is the target of both Amos and Jesus.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A type: &ldquo;I gave you empty mouths in all your cities and shortage of food in all your towns — yet you did not return to me, declares the LORD.&rdquo; The refrain &ldquo;yet you did not return to me&rdquo; (<em>wĕlōʾ-shavtem ʿaday</em>) repeats through vv. 6-11 — five cycles of warning-without-repentance. The NT applies this pattern to Jesus&rsquo;s own generation: &ldquo;He performed signs among them, yet they still did not believe in him&rdquo; (John 12:37). The hardening of those who refuse to return despite judgment is the pattern that Paul analyzes in Romans 9-11 using Pharaoh as the paradigm (Rom 9:17-18).</p>",
    "7": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;I also withheld the rain from you three months before harvest; I sent rain on one city but not another.&rdquo; The selective withdrawal of rain — one city rain, another dry — is YHWH&rsquo;s providential discipline. The NT uses weather-imagery for both blessing and judgment: &ldquo;He makes his sun rise on the evil and on the good, and sends rain on the just and on the unjust&rdquo; (Matt 5:45 — general blessing); but also &ldquo;I have this against you: you have abandoned the love you had at first... I will come to you and remove your lampstand from its place&rdquo; (Rev 2:4-5 — selective removal of blessing). Christ&rsquo;s parable of the Prodigal&rsquo;s elder brother lives in plenty while the younger son famishes — the same within-family economic differentiation as discipline.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Two or three cities staggered to another city for water and could not get enough — yet you did not return to me.&rdquo; The desperate seeking of water that cannot satisfy is the image Christ uses in the opposite direction: &ldquo;whoever drinks of the water that I will give him will never be thirsty again&rdquo; (John 4:14). Israel staggers to cisterns that are dry (Jer 2:13 uses the same image); Jesus offers the spring of living water. The inability to return to YHWH under discipline is resolved only by Christ, who makes return possible.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A shadow: blight, mildew, and locusts consuming gardens and vineyards — covenant curses from Deuteronomy 28:22, 38-42 arriving exactly as warned. The vine-and-garden imagery runs throughout the OT and NT as a symbol of Israel&rsquo;s covenant life. Jesus says, &ldquo;I am the true vine&rdquo; (John 15:1) — the antidote to the blighted vine of Amos; branches that abide in him bear fruit rather than being devoured by locusts. &ldquo;Yet you did not return to me&rdquo; — the refrain signals that only Christ, not discipline alone, produces genuine return.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;I sent among you a plague like those of Egypt; I killed your young men with the sword, took your horses... yet you did not return to me.&rdquo; The Egypt-plague comparison places Israel under the same judgment that fell on Pharaoh — the ultimate irony, since YHWH brought Israel <em>out</em> of Egypt and its plagues (2:10). The NT sees Christ as the one who passes through death-as-plague and emerges alive — the true Passover Lamb (1 Cor 5:7) who absorbs the plague-judgment that Israel continues to face under Amos.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A type: &ldquo;I overthrew some of you as God overthrew Sodom and Gomorrah; you were like a stick snatched from the fire.&rdquo; The Sodom-reference is the most extreme judgment-comparison available in the OT. Christ uses the same comparison: &ldquo;I tell you, it will be more bearable on that day for Sodom than for that town&rdquo; (Luke 10:12 — for towns that reject the apostles). The &ldquo;stick snatched from the fire&rdquo; becomes in Zechariah 3:2 the image of Joshua the high priest rescued from Satan — and ultimately of the elect who are snatched from the fire of judgment (Jude 23: &ldquo;save others by snatching them out of the fire&rdquo;).</p>",
    "12": "<p>A fulfillment-anticipation: &ldquo;Therefore, because I will do this to you, O Israel, prepare yourself to meet your God.&rdquo; The eschatological summons — prepare to meet God — is both threat and, for the repentant, invitation. The NT takes this up as the call to readiness for Christ&rsquo;s return: &ldquo;Therefore, stay awake, for you do not know on what day your Lord is coming&rdquo; (Matt 24:42). Meeting God in Amos is a prospect of judgment; meeting Christ in the NT is either terror or joy depending on one&rsquo;s standing before him. The preparation Christ calls for is faith and faithfulness, not merely fearful trembling.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A fulfillment: &ldquo;For this is he who forms the mountains and creates the wind, who reveals to humanity what he is thinking, who turns dawn into darkness and treads on the heights of the earth — the LORD God of Armies is his name.&rdquo; This hymnic doxology attributes creation, revelation, and cosmic sovereignty to YHWH. The NT applies all three attributes to Christ: creator (John 1:3: &ldquo;all things were made through him&rdquo;; Col 1:16); revealer (John 1:18; Heb 1:2: &ldquo;through whom also he created the world&rdquo; and &ldquo;in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son&rdquo;); and sovereign over creation (Matt 8:27: &ldquo;even the winds and sea obey him&rdquo;). Amos&rsquo;s creator-God and the NT&rsquo;s Christ are identified.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Hear this word — the funeral song I take up over you, O house of Israel.&rdquo; Amos sings a <em>qînāh</em> (lament-dirge) over Israel while they are still alive — a prophetic speech-act that treats the coming disaster as already accomplished. The only comparable NT scene is Jesus weeping over Jerusalem: &ldquo;Would that you, even you, had known on this day the things that make for peace! But now they are hidden from your eyes... because you did not know the time of your visitation&rdquo; (Luke 19:41-44). Both Amos and Jesus lament the city that is heading toward avoidable destruction; both laments are simultaneously prophecies of what will come.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A type: &ldquo;She has fallen, never to rise again — the virgin Israel; abandoned on her own land, with no one to lift her up.&rdquo; The fallen-and-unlifted language is the starkest image of Israel&rsquo;s coming defeat. Simeon&rsquo;s prophecy applies the same falling/rising pattern to Christ&rsquo;s effect: &ldquo;this child is destined for the falling and rising of many in Israel&rdquo; (Luke 2:34). The one who is destined to cause rising is also himself the risen one — Christ, who was himself brought low (&ldquo;he humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death,&rdquo; Phil 2:8) and raised by the Father (Phil 2:9), becomes the one who lifts up the fallen.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A shadow: the city that sent out a thousand men will have a hundred survive; the city that sent out a hundred will have ten left. The decimation pattern is the covenant curse for military defeat (Lev 26:8 inverted). The remnant-motif again: ten percent survive. Paul quotes the remnant principle from Isaiah but grounds it in Christ: &ldquo;Though the number of the sons of Israel be as the sand of the sea, only a remnant of them will be saved&rdquo; (Rom 9:27, citing Isa 10:22). The reduction from thousands to hundreds to tens is the eschatological narrowing that makes Christ&rsquo;s preservation of his flock all the more striking: &ldquo;I shall lose nothing of all that he has given me&rdquo; (John 6:39).</p>",
    "4": "<p>A fulfillment: &ldquo;For this is what the LORD says to the house of Israel: Seek me and live.&rdquo; The invitation is direct and unconditional — seek YHWH himself, not sanctuaries or ritual, and live. Christ issues the same invitation in its fullest form: &ldquo;Truly, truly, I say to you, whoever hears my word and believes him who sent me has eternal life. He does not come into judgment, but has passed from death to life&rdquo; (John 5:24). The &ldquo;live&rdquo; of Amos 5:4 is the <em>ḥāyāh</em> (life in its fullest covenant sense); the eternal life of John 5:24 is the eschatological fulfillment of exactly this promise.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Do not seek Bethel; do not go to Gilgal or travel to Beersheba — for Gilgal will certainly go into exile and Bethel will become a disaster.&rdquo; The command to avoid the sanctuaries — which would seem to be the places to seek God — is the prophetic subversion of institutional religion when it has become a substitute for genuine encounter. Jesus extends this logic to all geographical-cultic centers: &ldquo;Woman, believe me, the hour is coming when neither on this mountain nor in Jerusalem will you worship the Father&rdquo; (John 4:21). The sanctuary-without-God is replaced by worship in spirit and truth through Christ, who is himself the new temple (John 2:21).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A fulfillment: &ldquo;Seek the LORD and live, or he will sweep through the house of Joseph like a fire, devouring it with no one to quench it for Bethel.&rdquo; The double summons — seek and live — is the prophetic gospel before the gospel. The sweeping fire is the judgment that awaits those who refuse. The NT holds both: &ldquo;For God so loved the world, that he gave his only Son, that whoever believes in him should not perish but have eternal life&rdquo; (John 3:16) — the same life-or-perish structure, with Christ as the one who makes life possible and who will execute judgment on the unresponsive (John 3:36).</p>",
    "7": "<p>A type: &ldquo;You who twist justice into bitter poison and hurl righteousness to the ground.&rdquo; The twisting of justice (<em>laʿanāh</em>, wormwood — the bitter plant of curse) and the grounding of righteousness is the corruption of the covenant order. Christ comes to right exactly this inversion: &ldquo;He will not break a bruised reed or quench a smoldering wick, until he brings justice to victory&rdquo; (Matt 12:20, citing Isa 42:3). The establishment of justice is the central task of the Servant; Amos&rsquo;s charge against Israel makes Christ&rsquo;s justice-work the necessary response to the world&rsquo;s distortion of it.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A fulfillment: &ldquo;He who made the Pleiades and Orion, who turns deep darkness into dawn and darkens the day into night, who calls for the waters of the sea and pours them out over the face of the earth — the LORD is his name.&rdquo; This creator-doxology is applied in the NT to Christ without ambiguity: &ldquo;For by him all things were created, in heaven and on earth, visible and invisible&rdquo; (Col 1:16). The one who made the star-clusters (Pleiades/Orion) and controls the hydrological cycle is the Lord who becomes flesh. The turning of darkness into dawn is the literal pattern of Easter morning — &ldquo;early on the first day of the week, while it was still dark&rdquo; (John 20:1), darkness turning into the dawn of resurrection.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;He sends destruction flashing against the powerful so that ruin comes upon the fortified city.&rdquo; The divine warrior motif — God who strikes the powerful and the fortified — is the inverse of human military power. The NT&rsquo;s &ldquo;foolishness of God&rdquo; passage applies this: &ldquo;God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong; God chose what is low and despised in the world&rdquo; (1 Cor 1:27-28). Christ on the cross is the destruction that &ldquo;flashes against the powerful&rdquo; — the Roman imperial execution system is the fortified city that ruin comes upon, because what it intends as defeat becomes the world&rsquo;s redemption.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A type: &ldquo;They hate the judge who rebukes them at the gate and despise the one who tells the truth.&rdquo; The gate was the ancient courtroom — rebuke at the gate is official judicial correction. The hating of the truth-teller is the pattern that Jesus embodies and predicts: &ldquo;If I tell the truth, why do you not believe me? Whoever is of God hears the words of God. The reason why you do not hear them is that you are not of God&rdquo; (John 8:46-47). The truth-speaker who is hated in Amos&rsquo;s gate is the type of the Truth (John 14:6) who is hated by the world (John 15:18).</p>",
    "11": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Because you crush the poor and impose a grain tax on him, you have built houses of dressed stone, but you will not live in them; you have planted delightful vineyards, but you will not drink their wine.&rdquo; The covenant curse — you build but will not inhabit, you plant but will not eat — reverses the blessing of Deuteronomy 28:30-33 (which was a blessing for obedience). Christ pronounces the same reversal on those who build systems of exploitation: &ldquo;Woe to you who are rich, for you have received your consolation&rdquo; (Luke 6:24). The stone houses are abandoned; what endures is the house not built by human hands (2 Cor 5:1).</p>",
    "12": "<p>A type: &ldquo;I know how numerous your crimes are and how great your sins — you who oppress the innocent, accept bribes, and deny justice to the needy at the gate.&rdquo; The divine omniscience of Israel&rsquo;s crimes — &ldquo;I know&rdquo; — establishes that the Judge is fully informed. The NT extends this: &ldquo;Nothing in all creation is hidden from God&rsquo;s sight. Everything is uncovered and laid bare before the eyes of him to whom we must give account&rdquo; (Heb 4:13). The one who knows Israel&rsquo;s crimes is Christ, who also knows his own people perfectly: &ldquo;I know my own and my own know me&rdquo; (John 10:14). The same divine knowledge that condemns the unjust assures the just.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Therefore the wise man stays silent at a time like this, for it is an evil time.&rdquo; The silence of the wise — in an evil time when speech is dangerous — is a transitional verse. Jesus himself is silent before his accusers at key moments: &ldquo;But he gave him no answer, not even to a single charge, so that the governor was greatly amazed&rdquo; (Matt 27:14). The silence of the servant under unjust power (Isa 53:7: &ldquo;he opened not his mouth&rdquo;) is the redemptive counterpart to Amos&rsquo;s prudential silence — Christ&rsquo;s silence is not self-protective but sacrificial.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A fulfillment: &ldquo;Seek good and not evil, that you may live; and then the LORD, the God of armies, will be with you as you have said.&rdquo; The conditional &ldquo;God with us&rdquo; — <em>ʿimmanū ʾĕlōhîm</em> in structure — anticipates Emmanuel. Isaiah gives it a name (Isa 7:14: <em>ʿImmānūʾēl</em>); Matthew identifies its fulfillment: &ldquo;Behold, the virgin shall conceive and bear a son, and they shall call his name Immanuel (which means, God with us)&rdquo; (Matt 1:23). Amos&rsquo;s conditional &ldquo;God will be with you if you seek good&rdquo; becomes, in Christ, the unconditional gift: God with us in the incarnate Son, regardless of whether Israel has first earned the condition.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A fulfillment: &ldquo;Hate evil and love good; establish justice at the gate — perhaps the LORD, the God of armies, will be gracious to the remnant of Joseph.&rdquo; The &ldquo;perhaps&rdquo; (<em>ʾûlay</em>) of Amos — YHWH&rsquo;s grace is uncertain given Israel&rsquo;s track record — becomes certainty in Christ. &ldquo;The remnant of Joseph&rdquo; is the northern tribe stripped almost bare; Paul identifies the remnant chosen by grace: &ldquo;So too at the present time there is a remnant, chosen by grace. But if it is by grace, it is no longer on the basis of works&rdquo; (Rom 11:5-6). The &ldquo;perhaps&rdquo; of Amos is resolved into the certainty of election in Christ — grace is the ground, not the reward for hating evil.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Therefore in all the public squares there will be wailing, and in every street they will say, &lsquo;Alas! Alas!&rsquo;&rdquo; The universal lament — wailing in every plaza and street — is the sound of the Day of the LORD falling on Israel. The NT reserves the same sound for the eschatological day: &ldquo;Then all the tribes of the earth will mourn, and they will see the Son of Man coming on the clouds of heaven with power and great glory&rdquo; (Matt 24:30; citing Zech 12:10-14). The wailing is both Israel&rsquo;s consequence for rejecting the prophetic word and the mourning of those who see Christ&rsquo;s return as judgment rather than salvation.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;There will be wailing in every vineyard, for I will pass through your midst, declares the LORD.&rdquo; The passing-through of YHWH in judgment echoes the Passover — YHWH passed through Egypt to strike the firstborn (Exod 12:12). Now YHWH passes through Israel in the same judgment-mode. The Passover-and-exodus logic is reversed: Israel is in the place of Egypt. Christ&rsquo;s blood as Passover Lamb (1 Cor 5:7) is the means by which the destroyer passes over those who trust him — the one mark that makes the difference between the judgment that wails in the vineyard and the life that survives it.</p>",
    "18": "<p>A fulfillment: &ldquo;Woe to you who long for the day of the LORD! Why would you want the day of the LORD? It is darkness, not light.&rdquo; Israel expects the Day of the LORD to bring vindication against its enemies; Amos announces it brings judgment on Israel itself. The NT makes the same reversal about those who assume Christ&rsquo;s return will vindicate their position: &ldquo;Not everyone who says to me, &lsquo;Lord, Lord,&rsquo; will enter the kingdom of heaven&rdquo; (Matt 7:21). The Day turns out to be darkness for those who expected light — a warning that applies to every generation that assumes proximity to the form of religion equals protection from its substance.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;It will be like a man who fled from a lion and ran into a bear, or escaped into his house and put his hand on the wall and a serpent bit him.&rdquo; The inescapability of the Day of the LORD — every escape route leads to a worse danger — is a darkly comic parable. The NT counterpart is Revelation&rsquo;s fifth trumpet: &ldquo;In those days people will seek death and will not find it. They will long to die, and death will flee from them&rdquo; (Rev 9:6). The extreme of the inescapable judgment that Amos describes in earthly terms becomes in Revelation the anguish of the final judgment. Christ alone is the door that opens to escape: &ldquo;I am the door. If anyone enters by me, he will be saved&rdquo; (John 10:9).</p>",
    "20": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Is not the day of the LORD darkness and not light — pitch dark, with no gleam of brightness?&rdquo; The definitive answer to the rhetorical question: absolute darkness, no exception. The cross was accompanied by exactly this literal darkness: &ldquo;Now from the sixth hour there was darkness over all the land until the ninth hour&rdquo; (Matt 27:45). The cosmic darkness at the crucifixion is the Day of the LORD&rsquo;s darkness falling on the Son — he bears the pitch-dark judgment so that those who trust him live in the light: &ldquo;I am the light of the world. Whoever follows me will not walk in darkness&rdquo; (John 8:12).</p>",
    "21": "<p>A fulfillment: &ldquo;I hate and despise your religious festivals; I take no pleasure in your solemn gatherings.&rdquo; The divine rejection of festival-worship divorced from covenant ethics is the sharpest prophetic critique of institutional religion. Jesus applies this directly: &ldquo;You have made void the word of God for the sake of your tradition&rdquo; (Matt 15:6). His cleansing of the temple at Passover (John 2:13-17) is the enacted form of Amos&rsquo;s declaration — the festival has become a system that God despises. What God desires instead is visible in Christ, who embodies both perfect worship and perfect justice.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Even when you bring me burnt offerings and grain offerings, I will not accept them; when you offer your fellowship offerings of fattened cattle, I will not look on them.&rdquo; The refusal of Israel&rsquo;s sacrifices is the inverse of the perfect sacrifice Christ offers. Hebrews makes this contrast explicit: &ldquo;For it is impossible for the blood of bulls and goats to take away sins&rdquo; (Heb 10:4) — not because sacrifice is wrong in principle, but because animal sacrifice divorced from the heart and from justice is what Amos condemns, and what Christ replaces with the one acceptable offering: himself (Heb 10:10: &ldquo;by that will we have been sanctified through the offering of the body of Jesus Christ once for all&rdquo;).</p>",
    "23": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Away with the noise of your songs! I will not listen to the music of your harps.&rdquo; The silencing of Israel&rsquo;s worship-music is the rejection of music performed by unjust hands. The NT offers the corrective: true worship is &ldquo;singing and making melody to the Lord with your heart&rdquo; (Eph 5:19) — heart-worship flowing from lives of justice and love, not external performance. Revelation&rsquo;s vision of true worship (Rev 5:9: &ldquo;they sang a new song&rdquo;) contrasts with Amos&rsquo;s silenced harps: the new song is sung by those washed in Christ&rsquo;s blood, whose lives the silenced harps pointed toward.</p>",
    "24": "<p>A fulfillment: &ldquo;But let justice roll down like waters, and righteousness like an ever-flowing stream.&rdquo; The most quoted verse in Amos is the positive vision after the negative rejection: what God wants is ceaseless, life-giving justice. The eschatological river of justice finds its NT home in both the kingdom of God and in Christ himself: &ldquo;Whoever believes in me, as the Scripture has said, &lsquo;Out of his heart will flow rivers of living water&rsquo;&rdquo; (John 7:38). Christ is the source from which justice-as-water flows. Revelation 22:1-2 pictures the river of life flowing from the throne of God and of the Lamb — the ever-flowing stream of Amos 5:24 in its final eschatological form.</p>",
    "25": "<p>A shadow: &ldquo;Did you bring me sacrifices and offerings during the forty years in the wilderness, O house of Israel?&rdquo; The rhetorical question challenges Israel&rsquo;s assumption that the sacrificial system is ancient and foundational. Stephen cites this verse in Acts 7:42-43 in his speech before the Sanhedrin, applying it to Israel&rsquo;s history of apostasy and leading to his indictment: &ldquo;you always resist the Holy Spirit&rdquo; (Acts 7:51). The wilderness period was characterized more by grumbling and idol-worship than by faithful sacrifice — the point Amos makes and Stephen repeats in the face of the council that is about to stone him.</p>",
    "26": "<p>A fulfillment: &ldquo;You carried your shrine of Sikkuth your king and Kiyyun your star-god — the idols you made for yourselves.&rdquo; Stephen cites this verse (Amos 5:26) in Acts 7:43 (using the LXX, which reads &ldquo;Moloch&rdquo; and &ldquo;Rephan&rdquo;) as the culmination of Israel&rsquo;s idolatry in the wilderness. The idolatry of star-worship — carrying astral-deity shrines while nominally worshiping YHWH — is the pattern of syncretism that the NT confronts in the form of Gentile idolatry (Acts 17:22-23: the Athenian altar to an unknown god; Paul redirects this to Christ) and Jewish compromise. The only true star-god is Christ, &ldquo;the bright morning star&rdquo; (Rev 22:16).</p>",
    "27": "<p>A fulfillment-anticipation: &ldquo;Therefore I will send you into exile beyond Damascus, says the LORD, whose name is the God of armies.&rdquo; The exile-beyond-Damascus is the Assyrian exile of 722 BCE — the fate of the northern kingdom that refused to return to YHWH through five cycles of discipline (chs. 4). Stephen uses this verse (Acts 7:43 cites the LXX version &ldquo;beyond Babylon&rdquo;) to argue that Israel&rsquo;s exile was the consequence of persistent idolatry, and that the Jerusalem establishment of his day is repeating the same pattern in rejecting Christ. The exile announced in Amos becomes in the NT the paradigm for understanding what it means to reject God&rsquo;s appointed messengers — culminating in the rejection of the Messenger himself.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'amos')
    merge_comm(existing, AMOS_CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'amos', existing)
    print('Amos 1–5 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
